{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531162"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14581"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14581"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.38,0.1,0.36,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62681"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"4855"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35514"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43540"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45972"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62681"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three days of severe neck pain and reduced range of movement. She has recently undergone multiple steroid nerve root injections to her left shoulder for osteoarthritis with minimal benefit. She has a medical history of osteoarthritis, gout, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, ischaemic heart disease, dyslipidaemia, chronic kidney disease (stage 3), osteoporosis and glaucoma. Her regular medications include metformin, perindopril, amlodipine, atorvastatin, aspirin, and timolol eye drops. Several medications were recently ceased due to polypharmacy concerns, including allopurinol which she had been taking for five years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has reduced range of movement in the neck in all directions and is tender over her midline C4 joint. Neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 128 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 8.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 290 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 80 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate: 50 mm/hr (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 145 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate: 35 mL/min/1.73m2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EX-ray of the cervical spine shows degenerative changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septic arthritis","Spinal gout","Osteoarthritis","Cervical spondylitis","Polymyalgia rheumatica"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute neck pain shortly after cessation of allopurinol, with elevated inflammatory markers and a background of multiple risk factors for gout. While cervical spine involvement is uncommon, \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal gout\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered, particularly given the recent withdrawal of allopurinol which can precipitate acute attacks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic degenerative condition that typically causes mechanical pain that worsens with activity and improves with rest. While this patient has radiological evidence of cervical spine osteoarthritis, the acute onset, elevated inflammatory markers, and temporal relationship to allopurinol cessation make this unlikely to be the cause of the current presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyalgia rheumatica\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with shoulder and hip girdle pain and stiffness, rather than isolated cervical spine involvement. While inflammatory markers would be elevated, the history of allopurinol cessation points to a different diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more severe systemic symptoms including fever, and higher inflammatory markers. The patient is not systemically unwell enough for this diagnosis, even with recent history of steroid injections to surrounding joint. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical spondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause neck pain and stiffness but would not explain the acute presentation or the relationship to allopurinol cessation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for gout in this patient include chronic kidney disease, diabetes, and use of diuretics (likely as part of her cardiac medications). The recent cessation of allopurinol, which is a common target for deprescribing in elderly patients, can lead to rebound hyperuricemia and precipitation of acute gout in unusual locations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Discontinuation of allopurinol can precipitate acute gout, including in atypical locations such as the cervical spine.","Elderly patients with multiple comorbidities, particularly chronic kidney disease, are at increased risk of gout.","Spinal gout should be considered in patients with unexplained joint pain and a history of gout risk factors."],"references":["Afinogenova Y, Danve A, Neogi T. Update on gout management: what is old and what is new. Current opinion in rheumatology. 2022 Mar 1;34(2):118-24. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8799507/","Coleshill MJ, Day RO, Tam K, et al. Persistence with urate-lowering therapy in Australia: A longitudinal analysis of allopurinol prescriptions. Br J Clin Pharmacol. 2022;88(11):4894-4901. doi:10.1111/bcp.15435 Available online at ; https://bpspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/pdfdirect/10.1111/bcp.15435","Spragg JC, Michael TJ, Aslani P, Coleshill MJ, Chan JS, Day RO, Stocker SL. Optimizing adherence to allopurinol for gout: patients\u0027 perspectives. British Journal of Clinical Pharmacology. 2023 Jul;89(7):1978-91. Available online at ; https://bpspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/bcp.15657"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14581"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T10:10:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T10:28:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7274"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62681"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":